# Normalize line endings. Without this, cloning on Windows with Git's
# default core.autocrlf=true rewrites text files to CRLF on checkout — and a
# shell script with CRLF endings breaks under bash on Linux/WSL/containers
# with: "$'\r': command not found" / "set: pipefail: invalid option name".
#
# `text=auto` lets git store everything LF-normalized in the repo while still
# checking out the platform's native endings for ordinary text. Shell scripts
# are pinned to LF on every platform so bash never sees a stray carriage
# return, no matter how the clone is configured.
* text=auto
*.sh text eol=lf
